# trusted-signers.example — template for the signed-update trust anchor
#
# Copy this file to `trusted-signers` (same name, no .example) and put your real
# SSH PUBLIC signing key on one line to ACTIVATE verified self-updates. When
# `trusted-signers` is present, the updater (update-system.mjs) only applies
# release tags whose signature verifies against a key listed here; it ignores any
# tag (even a higher version) that is unsigned or signed by a different key.
#
# This file ships INSIDE the installer bundle and is deliberately NOT self-updated,
# so it is a fixed trust anchor: it can only change when you build and ship a new
# .exe. An SSH PUBLIC key is safe to commit publicly.
#
# Format (OpenSSH allowed-signers), one signer per line:
#   <tagger-email> namespaces="git" <key-type> <base64-key>
#
# <tagger-email> MUST match the identity git records when you sign a tag
# (git config user.email; for a GitHub noreply email, use that exact address).
# Example (replace with your real key):
#
# you@example.com namespaces="git" ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAA...yourkey...
#
# See docs/RELEASING.md for the full activation + signing runbook.
